A river that begins in Westchester County, New York in a series of ponds at about 183 m altitude. It passes through the Mianus River Gorge, a nature preserve, before entering Fairfield County, Connecticut, where it is dammed into the Mianus Reservoir (78 m altitude). From there, it flows south through Greenwich and Stamford into Long Island Sound, at sea level.
A river in the town of Fairfield, Connecticut. It flows into Long Island Sound at Southport Harbor.

A river in southwestern Connecticut. The Norwalk River originates in ponds located in Ridgefield, Connecticut. These ponds empty into the Great Swamp in Ridgefied. The river continues through Ridgefield, and is augmented by the Great Pond, one of the purest lakes in Connecticut due to its being fed by underwater springs. The river is closely paralleled by US Route 7 as it flows southward through Branchville, Georgetown, Wilton, and Norwalk, where it is joined by the Silvermine River and then flows into Norwalk Harbor and finally into Long Island Sound.

A river in southwestern Connecticut in the United States. It issues from Wataba Lake (562 feet above sea level) approximately 6 km southwest of Danbury near the New York border. It flows generally southeast, passing through the Saugatuck Reservoir (283 feet above sea level), then turns SSW. Near Westport, it broadens into a navigable estuary along its lower 8 km and enters Long Island Sound approximately 6 km southeast of Norwalk.

A river in the New England region of the United States, located entirely in the state of Connecticut. It rises in west central Connecticut from Dead Wood Swamp west of the city of New Britain. It flows roughly southward to Plainville, Southington, west of the city of Meriden, Cheshire,through Wallingford and Yalesville,North Haven, and flows into New Haven Harbor, an inlet of Long Island Sound, east of downtown New Haven.
A river in southern Connecticut. It flows through the towns of Bethany, Woodbridge, and New Haven before discharging into the West Haven Harbor.

A river located in the state of Connecticut in New Haven County. It flows south through Orange and forms the boundary of West Haven and Orange and further downstream the boundary of West Haven and Milford. It empties into Long Island Sound, just south of Route 162 at Oyster River Point.

A river in southeast New York and southwestern Connecticut in the United States. Its headwaters are at Byram Lake in Westchester County, New York, and flows in a southward direction, crossing the New York-Connecticut border and eventually reaching sea level at Port Chester Harbor, where it empties into the Long Island Sound.

A river that is formed about 4 miles southeast of Durham, Connecticut along a gulley on the north end of Bunker Hill at about a half mile northeast of the junction of Route 148 and Bunker Hill Road. The river travels for about 20 miles to Clinton Harbor on Long Island Sound just east of Hammonasset Beach State Park.
A river that is formed at a swampy drainage about 3.2 km north of Westford, Connecticut and flows about 23.3 km to Mansfield Hollow Lake just south of Atwoodville, Connecticut.

A river in southwestern Connecticut and souththat drains in to the Titicus Reservoir. The source of the river is in Ridgefield, Connecticut. About 1 mile down stream, the stream marks the southern boundary of the Kiahs Brook Reserve. Another 0.5 miles downriver, it joins with Kiahs Brook, and then runs fairly close to Route 116. Once past the New York border, the Titicus River still runs close to New York 116, until discharging to the Titicus Reservoir.
A river draining into Long Island Sound between Bluff Point State Park (to the E) and Groton-New London Airport (to the W).
